From: hmaarrfk <mark.harfouche@conda-forge.org>
Date: 2026-06-04
Subject: npu_compiler: keep newer-GCC -Werror diagnostics non-fatal

npu_compiler compiles its targets with `-Wall -Wextra -Werror` (see
cmake/compile_options.cmake). conda-forge builds this against the
vendored LLVM/MLIR fork with a newer GCC (14.3) at -O3 than the compiler
Intel's CI uses, which turns two classes of diagnostic into hard errors:

  * Well-known GCC false-positive warnings in LLVM/MLIR's heavily
    templated container/move code, e.g.
      DenseMap.h: error: '...DenseSetPair<int>**)TmpEnd)[2]' may be used
        uninitialized [-Werror=maybe-uninitialized]
      iti_buffer.cpp:312: error: possibly dangling reference to a
        temporary [-Werror=dangling-reference]

  * The stricter C++20 conformance diagnostic -Wtemplate-id-cdtor for
    ill-formed-but-unambiguous `Name<T>()` constructor / destructor
    spellings in several IE/VPUIP passes, e.g.
      adapt_shapes_for_scale_shift.cpp:39 / adjust_fake_qdq_params.cpp:307
      error: template-id not allowed for constructor in C++20

None of these are defects that affect the produced libraries, and they
do not reproduce on the older compiler upstream validates against. Keep
the diagnostics as warnings but stop the bare -Werror from failing the
build on this known set. Scoped to GCC via generator expressions (Clang
lacks these); GCC silently ignores any -Wno-error= name it does not
recognise, so the list is safe across GCC versions.

--- a/cmake/compile_options.cmake
+++ b/cmake/compile_options.cmake
@@ -115,6 +115,27 @@
         target_compile_options(${TARGET_NAME}
             PRIVATE
                 -Wall -Wextra -Werror -Werror=suggest-override
+                # conda-forge builds this with a newer GCC (14) at -O3 than
+                # Intel's CI uses. That surfaces (a) a family of well-known
+                # GCC false-positive warnings in the vendored LLVM/MLIR
+                # template and container code (DenseMap/DenseSet moves,
+                # dangling references to temporaries, ...) and (b) a stricter
+                # C++20 conformance diagnostic, template-id-cdtor, for the
+                # ill-formed-but-unambiguous `Name<T>()` constructor /
+                # destructor spellings used in several IE/VPUIP passes. The
+                # bare -Werror above turns all of these into hard errors.
+                # Keep the warnings but make this known set non-fatal. GCC
+                # only (Clang lacks these); GCC silently ignores any
+                # -Wno-error= name it does not recognise, so this is safe
+                # across GCC versions.
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=maybe-uninitialized>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=dangling-reference>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=array-bounds>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=stringop-overflow>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=stringop-overread>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=restrict>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=uninitialized>
+                $<$<CXX_COMPILER_ID:GNU>:-Wno-error=template-id-cdtor>
         )
         # Set SYSTEM property on OpenVINO dependencies to suppress extra warnings from their headers
         # when building via OPENVINO_EXTRA_MODULES
